{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CGtcY4o4pGkopLEAUNgLzS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior for the webhook handler system and determine the appropriate test level.\n\nThe system:\n- Node.js service\n- Receives webhooks with `X-Signature-256` HMAC-SHA256 header\n- Validates signature against raw request body\n- Acknowledges immediately (HTTP 200)\n- Forwards to internal processing queue for async handling\n- Must be idempotent (no duplicate enqueue)\n- Must handle slow downstream processing\n\nLet me go through each behavior:\n\n**Behavior 1: Signature validation → 401 rejection**\n- This is pure HMAC verification logic: compute HMAC of body, compare with header\n\n\n- The validation function itself is pure logic with no I/O or network calls, but testing the actual behavior requires verifying that the HTTP handler returns a 401 response, which crosses the handler boundary. This makes it an Integration test—I'm checking that the validation logic and HTTP response layer work together correctly.\n- For Node.js, I can use supertest to wire up the app without a real network, which is the practical way to test this at the Integration level.\n- Now looking at the second behavior: ensuring the event is written to the queue before the HTTP 200 response is sent back.\n- This is about the ordering between queue.enqueue() and res.send(200), which crosses module boundaries.\n- I'd need an Integration test that instruments both the queue and the response path to verify the ordering, using mocked queue implementations and supertest.\n- For the third behavior: the handler should return the HTTP response without waiting for downstream processing to complete.\n- This is testing async fire-and-forget wiring—I can mock the downstream processor to be intentionally slow and verify the response comes back quickly, which is still an Integration test since there's no real network involved.\n\nFor the fourth behavior about response timing under concurrent load: I'm weighing whether this needs Integration or System level testing. With supertest and mocked slow downstream, I can send concurrent requests and measure wall-clock timing, but the real concurrency behavior under the Node.js event loop might require a real HTTP server to properly validate.\n\nFor idempotency with event IDs: The dedup logic sits at a module boundary between the ID store and queue, so I need Integration testing with both wired together to catch failures there.\n\nFor the queue-full scenario: The handler needs to catch the \"full\" error from the queue and respond with 503 plus Retry-After header. This is another module boundary that requires Integration testing with a mocked queue throwing that error.\n\nFor capacity enforcement itself: The persistent queue's own logic needs to actually reject writes when at capacity. If it's backed by a real data store, I might need Integration testing with the actual storage layer, though a local in-process store would be sufficient to verify the capacity logic works correctly.\n\nOn behavior 4, I'm reconsidering whether the concurrency and timing requirements really push this to System level. Supertest can handle concurrent requests, so Integration testing with the real handler under load should be enough to verify the 3-second constraint holds even with slow downstream processing happening in parallel.\n\nLooking at the full set of behaviors, most map to Integration tests since they involve the queue implementation and HTTP handler working together. But behavior 1 is interesting—the HMAC validation itself is pure crypto logic that I could test at Unit level with mocked HTTP context, just verifying the validation function rejects invalid signatures and that the queue mock never gets called when validation fails. Looking at the test classification more carefully, I can unit test the handler with spies to verify operation ordering—queue.enqueue() gets called before res.send()—without needing a full integration setup. That said, relying on spy assertions for async ordering feels fragile compared to actually running the code end-to-end, so integration testing is probably the safer bet for behavior 2.\n\nFor the queue capacity enforcement, \"persistent queue\" suggests I'm testing against a real backing store rather than an in-memory mock, which pushes this toward integration testing.\n\nLooking at behavior 4 again—the wall-clock timing under concurrent requests—I'm reconsidering whether integration is sufficient or if I need a full system test. The timing assertion requires actual concurrency and real HTTP semantics, which supertest can handle with concurrent agents, but I'm uncertain whether that's enough to reliably test the 3-second guarantee across different execution environments.\n\nI'll stick with Integration for now, though I acknowledge it's borderline with System testing.\n\nSettling on my final classifications: Unit, Integration, Integration, Integration (with System as a close alternative), Integration, Integration, and Integration. Now I'm assigning confidence levels to each—behavior 1 is solidly Unit but has some chance of needing integration coverage, behavior 4 is the most uncertain with nearly equal odds between Integration and System, and the rest lean heavily toward Integration with minor uncertainty around edge cases.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":12681,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":12681},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e6eddda0-2099-4f30-a621-de97d7a6e354","uuid":"8c13bf34-8e16-48bd-b634-d9166fd25117"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CGtcY4o4pGkopLEAUNgLzS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01LDQG6FyEdN4rduqBduxABe","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Request with mismatched signature is rejected with 401; body not forwarded.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The failure is entirely within a single handler function: compute HMAC of raw body, compare with header, return 401 and skip enqueue. In Node.js this can be exercised with a mock req/res and a spy on the queue—no real HTTP server or module handoff is needed. The 'not forwarded' assertion is captured by verifying the queue spy was never called.","test_description":"Call the handler function directly with a mock req (body + wrong X-Signature-256 header, correct secret in config) and mock res. Assert res.status was called with 401, and the queue enqueue spy was never invoked. Also test the inverse (correct signature) passes through.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.6,"Integration":0.35,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Event is written to the persistent queue before HTTP 200 is returned.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS applies: the ordering guarantee only matters at the boundary between the async queue write and the HTTP response path. A unit test with a synchronous mock queue trivially passes regardless of actual ordering. You need the real async queue module (or a real async test double that resolves on its own tick) wired to the handler to observe that res.send() is not called until after enqueue() resolves.","test_description":"Wire the handler with the real (or locally running) persistent queue. Instrument queue.enqueue to record its completion timestamp and override res.send to record when the response is sent. Send a valid signed request via supertest and assert that the enqueue completion timestamp precedes the response send timestamp.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Handler returns HTTP response without waiting for downstream processing to finish.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: the failure only surfaces when the downstream processor is a real async unit that can be observed to still be running after the response is sent. A unit test where the downstream is a synchronous mock cannot distinguish fire-and-forget from blocking await. You need the handler wired with a controllable async downstream (e.g., a promise held open) to verify the response arrives before downstream completes.","test_description":"Register a downstream processor that holds a deferred promise open for 2 seconds. Send a valid request via supertest, record the response time, then let the deferred resolve. Assert the response was received before the deferred resolved, confirming the handler did not await downstream.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Response arrives within 3 seconds wall-clock time even under concurrent load with slow downstream.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"REAL-INFRA check: the 3-second wall-clock constraint under concurrency requires real async scheduling, but Node.js in-process HTTP (supertest with a real listen port) provides genuine concurrent connection handling without needing an external server process. A slow downstream can be simulated with a long-lived deferred. The timer assertion must use real wall-clock time, making this Integration rather than Unit, but no OS subprocess or external network is strictly required.","test_description":"Start the handler app on a real in-process port. Configure downstream to delay 10 seconds. Fire 5 concurrent requests (Promise.all over 5 supertest calls) with valid signatures. Assert that all responses complete in under 3 seconds wall-clock (Date.now delta), regardless of the still-pending downstream tasks.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.45,"System":0.45,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"An event whose ID was already received is not written to the queue a second time.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: deduplication requires coordination between the ID-seen store and the queue write path. If both are mocked independently, you cannot catch a race condition or a missing check. The idempotency failure only appears when the real dedup store (in-memory map, Redis, or DB) is wired to the handler so that a second request with the same event ID is checked against actual stored state.","test_description":"Send two valid signed requests with identical event IDs through the handler (with a real or local dedup store and queue). Assert that queue.enqueue was called exactly once across both requests, and the second request returns 200 (acknowledged) without re-enqueuing.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"When the queue reports it is full, the handler returns 503 with a Retry-After header.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: the handler must correctly translate a 'queue full' error from the queue module into a 503 + Retry-After response. While the queue itself can be stubbed to throw a capacity error, the interaction between the queue module's error contract and the handler's error-handling branch is a module boundary. A pure unit test with a trivially rejecting mock is sufficient only if the error type/contract is stable; using the real queue (or a realistic stub with matching error shape) ensures the error contract is honored.","test_description":"Configure the queue to be at capacity (or stub enqueue to throw the queue-full error with the real error shape). Send a valid signed request via supertest. Assert response status is 503 and the Retry-After header is present with a positive integer value.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"The persistent queue enforces its configured capacity limit and rejects events that exceed it.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: this behavior tests the queue implementation itself, not the handler. The queue is 'persistent,' meaning it relies on a backing store (file, embedded DB, or similar). The capacity enforcement involves the queue's internal size-tracking against its actual stored state. A unit test of a size counter variable would miss bugs where the count diverges from backing-store reality. The real queue module must be exercised with its persistence layer to verify the rejection.","test_description":"Instantiate the persistent queue with capacity=3 against a local backing store. Enqueue 3 events successfully. Attempt a 4th enqueue and assert it throws (or returns) a capacity-exceeded error. Optionally verify the backing store still contains exactly 3 items.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":12681,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":12681},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e6eddda0-2099-4f30-a621-de97d